# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: esd-protection-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] ESD can create spectacular electric sparks (lightning, with the accompanying sound of thunder, is an example of a large-scale ESD event), but also less dramatic forms, which may be neither seen nor heard, yet still be large enough to cause damage to sensitive electronic devices.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Electric sparks require a field strength above approximately 4 million V/m in air, as notably occurs in lightning strikes.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Similar forms of electric discharge include corona discharge from sharp electrodes, brush discharge from blunt electrodes, etc.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] ESD can cause harmful effects of importance in industry, including explosions in gas, fuel vapor and coal dust, as well as failure of solid state electronics components such as integrated circuits.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] These can suffer permanent damage when subjected to high voltages.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Electronics manufacturers therefore establish electrostatic protective areas free of static, using measures to prevent charging, such as avoiding highly charging materials and measures to remove static such as grounding human workers, providing antistatic devices, and controlling humidity.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] ESD simulators may be used to test electronic devices, for example with a human body model or a charged device model.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] One of the causes of ESD events is static electricity.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Static electricity is often generated through tribocharging, the separation of electric charges that occurs when two materials are brought into contact and then separated.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Examples of tribocharging include walking on a rug, rubbing a plastic comb against dry hair, rubbing a balloon against a sweater, ascending from a fabric car seat, or removing some types of plastic packaging.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] In all these cases, the breaking of contact between two materials results in tribocharging, thus creating a difference of electrical potential that can lead to an ESD event.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Another cause of ESD damage is through electrostatic induction.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] This occurs when an electrically charged object is placed near a conductive object isolated from the ground.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] The presence of the charged object creates an electrostatic field that causes electrical charges on the surface of the other object to redistribute.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Even though the net electrostatic charge of the object has not changed, it now has regions of excess positive and negative charges.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] An ESD event may occur when the object comes into contact with a conductive path.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] For example, charged regions on the surfaces of styrofoam cups or bags can induce potential on nearby ESD sensitive components via electrostatic induction and an ESD event may occur if the component is touched with a metallic tool.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] ESD can also be caused by energetic charged particles impinging on an object.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] This causes increasing surface and deep charging.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] This is a known hazard for most spacecraft.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Electrostatic discharge (ESD) phenomena vary in complexity and magnitude, with the electric spark being the most visible and dramatic example.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] This occurs when a strong electric field ionizes the air, creating a conductive channel that can convey an electric current.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] People may experience this as a small jolt of discomfort, but ESD can inflict severe damage on electronic components, potentially leading to malfunctions and failures.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] In hazardous environments where flammable gases or dust particles are present, ESD can trigger fires or explosions.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Not all ESD events, however, are accompanied by a visible spark or noise.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] It is possible for a person to carry a charge that, while undetectable to the human senses, can still be potent enough to harm delicate electronics.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Some components can be compromised by discharges as faint as 30 V, with such damage sometimes not becoming apparent until significant usage has occurred, thus affecting the lifespan and performance of the devices.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Cable discharge events (CDEs) are discharges occurring when connecting electrical cables to a device.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] A spark is triggered when the electric field strength exceeds approximately 4–30 kV/cm—the dielectric field strength of air.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] This may cause a very rapid increase in the number of free electrons and ions in the air, temporarily causing the air to abruptly become an electrical conductor in a process called dielectric breakdown.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Perhaps the best known example of a natural spark is lightning.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] In this case the electric potential between a cloud and ground, or between two clouds, is typically hundreds of millions of volts.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] The resulting current that cycles through the stroke channel causes an enormous transfer of energy.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] On a much smaller scale, sparks can form in air during electrostatic discharges from charged objects that are charged to as little as 380 V (Paschen's law).
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Earth's atmosphere consists of 21% oxygen (O2) and 78% nitrogen (N2).
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] During an electrostatic discharge, such as a lightning flash, the affected atmospheric molecules become electrically overstressed.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] The diatomic oxygen molecules are split, and then recombine to form ozone (O3), which is unstable, or reacts with metals and organic matter.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] If the electrical stress is high enough, nitrogen oxides (NOx) can form.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Both products are toxic to animals, and nitrogen oxides are essential for nitrogen fixation.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Ozone attacks all organic matter by ozonolysis and is used in water purification.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Sparks are an ignition source in combustible environments that may lead to catastrophic explosions in concentrated fuel environments.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Most explosions can be traced back to a tiny electrostatic discharge, whether it was an unexpected combustible fuel leak invading a known open air sparking device, or an unexpected spark in a known fuel rich environment.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] The result is the same if oxygen is present and the three criteria of the fire triangle have been combined.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Many electronic components, especially integrated circuits and microchips, can be damaged by ESD.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Sensitive components need to be protected during and after manufacture, during shipping and device assembly, and in the finished device.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Grounding is especially important for effective ESD control.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] It should be clearly defined, and regularly evaluated.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] In manufacturing, prevention of ESD is based on an Electrostatic Discharge Protected Area (EPA).
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] The EPA can be a small workstation or a large manufacturing area.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] The main principle of an EPA is that there are no highly-charging materials in the vicinity of ESD sensitive electronics, all conductive and dissipative materials are grounded, workers are grounded, and charge build-up on ESD sensitive electronics is prevented.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] International standards are used to define a typical EPA and can be found for example from International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) or American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Humid conditions prevent electrostatic charge generation because the thin layer of moisture that accumulates on most surfaces serves to dissipate electric charges.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Ionizers are used especially when insulative materials cannot be grounded.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Ionization systems help to neutralize charged surface regions on insulative or dielectric materials.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Insulating materials prone to triboelectric charging of more than 2,000 V should be kept away at least 12 inches from sensitive devices to prevent accidental charging of devices through field induction.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] On aircraft, static dischargers are used on the trailing edges of wings and other surfaces.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Manufacturers and users of integrated circuits must take precautions to avoid ESD.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] ESD prevention can be part of the device itself and include special design techniques for device input and output pins.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] External protection components can also be used with circuit layout.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Due to dielectric nature of electronics component and assemblies, electrostatic charging cannot be completely prevented during handling of devices.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Most of ESD sensitive electronic assemblies and components are also so small that manufacturing and handling is done with automated equipment.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] ESD prevention activities are therefore important with those processes where components come into direct contact with equipment surfaces.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] In addition, it is important to prevent ESD when an electrostatic discharge sensitive component is connected with other conductive parts of the product itself.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] An efficient way to prevent ESD is to use materials that are not too conductive but will slowly conduct static charges away.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] These materials are called static dissipative and have resistivity values below 1012 ohm-meters.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Materials in automated manufacturing which will touch on conductive areas of ESD sensitive electronic should be made of dissipative material, and the dissipative material must be grounded.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] These special materials are able to conduct electricity, but do so very slowly.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Any built-up static charges dissipate without the sudden discharge that can harm the internal structure of silicon circuits.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Sensitive devices need to be protected during shipping, handling, and storage.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] The buildup and discharge of static can be minimized by controlling the surface resistance and volume resistivity of packaging materials.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Packaging is also designed to minimize frictional or triboelectric charging of packs due to rubbing together during shipping, and it may be necessary to incorporate electrostatic or electromagnetic shielding in the packaging material.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] A common example is that semiconductor devices and computer components are usually shipped in an antistatic bag made of a partially conductive plastic, which acts as a Faraday cage to protect the contents against ESD.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] For testing the susceptibility of electronic devices to ESD from human contact, an ESD Simulator with a special output circuit, called the human body model (HBM) is often used.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] This consists of a capacitor in series with a resistor.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] The capacitor is charged to a specified high voltage from an external source, and then suddenly discharged through the resistor into an electrical terminal of the device under test.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] One of the most widely used models is defined in the JEDEC 22-A114-B standard, which specifies a 100 picofarad capacitor and a 1,500 ohm resistor.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Other similar standards are MIL-STD-883 Method 3015, and the ESD Association's ESD STM5.1.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] For compliance to European Union standards for Information Technology Equipment, the IEC/EN 61000-4-2 test specification is used.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Another specification referenced by equipment maker Schaffner calls for C = 150 pF and R = 330 Ω which provides high fidelity results.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] While the theory is mostly there, very few companies measure the real ESD survival rate.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Guidelines and requirements are given for test cell geometries, generator specifications, test levels, discharge rate and waveform, types and points of discharge on the "victim" product, and functional criteria for gauging product survivability.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] A charged device model (CDM) test is used to define the ESD a device can withstand when the device itself has an electrostatic charge and discharges due to metal contact.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] This discharge type is the most common type of ESD in electronic devices and causes most of the ESD damages in their manufacturing.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] CDM discharge depends mainly on parasitic parameters of the discharge and strongly depends on size and type of component package.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] One of the most widely used CDM simulation test models is defined by the JEDEC.
[src:esd-protection-deep/electrostatic-discharge] Other standardized ESD test circuits include the machine model (MM) and transmission line pulse (TLP).
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] A **gas-filled tube**, also commonly known as a **discharge tube** or formerly as a **Plücker tube**, is an arrangement of electrodes in a gas within an insulating, temperature-resistant envelope.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Gas-filled tubes exploit phenomena related to electric discharge in gases, and operate by ionizing the gas with an applied voltage sufficient to cause electrical conduction by the underlying phenomena of the Townsend discharge.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] A gas-discharge lamp is an electric light using a gas-filled tube; these include fluorescent lamps, metal-halide lamps, sodium-vapor lamps, and neon lights.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Specialized gas-filled tubes such as krytrons, thyratrons, and ignitrons are used as switching devices in electric devices.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The voltage required to initiate and sustain discharge is dependent on the pressure and composition of the fill gas and geometry of the tube.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Although the envelope is typically glass, power tubes often use ceramics, and military tubes often use glass-lined metal.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Both hot cathode and cold cathode type devices are encountered.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Hydrogen is used in tubes used for very fast switching, e.g. some thyratrons, dekatrons, and krytrons, where very steep edges are required.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The build-up and recovery times of hydrogen are much shorter than in other gases.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Hydrogen thyratrons are usually hot-cathode.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Hydrogen (and deuterium) can be stored in the tube in the form of a metal hydride, heated with an auxiliary filament; hydrogen by heating such storage element can be used to replenish cleaned-up gas, and even to adjust the pressure as needed for a thyratron operation at a given voltage.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Deuterium is used in ultraviolet lamps for ultraviolet spectroscopy, in neutron generator tubes, and in special tubes (e.g. crossatron).
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] It has higher breakdown voltage than hydrogen.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] In fast switching tubes it is used instead of hydrogen where high voltage operation is required.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] For a comparison, the hydrogen-filled CX1140 thyratron has anode voltage rating of 25 kV, while the deuterium-filled and otherwise identical CX1159 has 33 kV.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Also, at the same voltage the pressure of deuterium can be higher than of hydrogen, allowing higher rise rates of current before it causes excessive anode dissipation.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Significantly higher peak powers are achievable.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Its recovery time is, however, about 40% slower than for hydrogen.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Noble gases are frequently used in tubes for many purposes, from lighting to switching.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Pure noble gases are employed in switching tubes.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Noble-gas-filled thyratrons have better electrical parameters than mercury-based ones.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The electrodes undergo damage by high-velocity ions.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The neutral atoms of the gas slow the ions down by collisions, and reduce the energy transferred to the electrodes by the ion impact.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Gases with high atomic weight, e.g. xenon, protect the electrodes better than lighter ones, e.g. neon.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] In special cases (e.g., high-voltage switches), gases with good dielectric properties and very high breakdown voltages are needed.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Highly electronegative elements, e.g., halogens, are favored as they rapidly recombine with the ions present in the discharge channel.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] One of the most popular choices is sulfur hexafluoride, used in special high-voltage applications.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Other common options are dry pressurized nitrogen and halocarbons.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The fundamental mechanism is the Townsend discharge, which is the sustained multiplication of electron flow by ion impact when a critical value of electric field strength for the density of the gas is reached.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] As the electric field is increased various phases of discharge are encountered as shown in the accompanying plot.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The gas used dramatically influences the parameters of the tube.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The breakdown voltage depends on the gas composition and electrode distance; the dependencies are described by Paschen's law.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The gas pressure may range between 0.001 and 1,000 Torr (0.13–130,000 Pa); most commonly, pressures between 1–10 torr are used.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Above a certain value, the higher the gas pressure, the higher the ignition voltage.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] High-pressure lighting tubes can require a few kilovolts impulse for ignition when cold, when the gas pressure is low.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] After warming up, when the volatile compound used for light emission is vaporized and the pressure increases, reignition of the discharge requires either significantly higher voltage or reducing the internal pressure by cooling down the lamp.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] For example, many sodium vapor lamps cannot be re-lit immediately after being shut off; they must cool down before they can be lit up again.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The gas tends to be used up during the tube operation, by several phenomena collectively called **clean-up**.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The gas atoms or molecules are adsorbed on the surfaces of the electrodes.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] In high voltage tubes, the accelerated ions can penetrate into the electrode materials.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] New surfaces, formed by sputtering of the electrodes and deposited on e.g. the inner surfaces of the tube, also readily adsorb gases.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Non-inert gases can also chemically react with the tube components.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Hydrogen may diffuse through some metals.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] For removal of gas in vacuum tubes, getters are used.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] For resupplying gas for gas-filled tubes, **replenishers** are employed.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The metal filament acts as a hydrogen storage.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] This approach is used in e.g. hydrogen thyratrons or neutron tubes.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Usage of saturated mercury vapor allows using a pool of liquid mercury as a large storage of material; the atoms lost by clean-up are automatically replenished by evaporation of more mercury.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The pressure in the tube is however strongly dependent on the mercury temperature, which has to be controlled carefully.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Large rectifiers use saturated mercury vapor with a small amount of an inert gas.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The inert gas supports the discharge when the tube is cold.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The mercury arc valve current-voltage characteristics are highly dependent on the temperature of the liquid mercury.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The voltage drop in forward bias decreases from about 60 volts at 0 °C to somewhat above 10 volts at 50 °C and then stays constant; the reverse bias breakdown ("arc-back") voltage drops dramatically with temperature, from 36 kV at 60 °C to 12 kV at 80 °C to even less at higher temperatures.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The operating range is therefore usually between 18–65 °C.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The gas in the tube has to be kept pure to maintain the desired properties; even small amount of impurities can dramatically change the tube values.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The presence of non-inert gases generally increases the breakdown and burning voltages.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The presence of impurities can be observed by changes in the glow color of the gas.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Air leaking into the tube introduces oxygen, which is highly electronegative and inhibits the production of electron avalanches.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] This makes the discharge look pale, milky, or reddish.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Traces of mercury vapors glow bluish, obscuring the original gas color.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Magnesium vapor colors the discharge green.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] To prevent outgassing of the tube components during operation, a bake-out is required before filling with gas and sealing.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Thorough degassing is required for high-quality tubes; even as little as 10−8 torr (≈1 μPa) of oxygen is sufficient for covering the electrodes with monomolecular oxide layer in few hours.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Non-inert gases can be removed by suitable getters.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] For mercury-containing tubes, getters that do not form amalgams with mercury (e.g. zirconium, but not barium) have to be used.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Cathode sputtering may be used intentionally for gettering non-inert gases; some reference tubes use molybdenum cathodes for this purpose.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Pure inert gases are used where the difference between the ignition voltage and the burning voltage has to be high, e.g. in switching tubes.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Tubes for indication and stabilization, where the difference has to be lower, tend to be filled with Penning mixtures; the lower difference between ignition and burning voltages allows using lower power supply voltages and smaller series resistances.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Fluorescent lighting, CFL lamps, mercury and sodium discharge lamps and HID lamps are all gas-filled tubes used for lighting.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Neon lamps and neon signage (most of which is not neon based these days) are also low-pressure gas-filled tubes.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Specialized historic low-pressure gas-filled tube devices include the Nixie tube (used to display numerals) and the Decatron (used to count or divide pulses, with display as a secondary function).
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Xenon flash lamps are gas-filled tubes used in cameras and strobe lights to produce bright flashes of light.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The recently developed sulfur lamps are also gas-filled tubes when hot.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Some important examples include the thyratron, krytron, and ignitron tubes, which are used to switch high-voltage currents.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] A specialized type of gas-filled tube called a gas discharge tube (GDT) is fabricated for use as surge protectors, to limit voltage surges in electrical and electronic circuits.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] The Schmitt trigger effect of the negative differential resistance-region can be exploited to realize timers, relaxation oscillators and digital circuits with neon lamps, *trigger tubes*, *relay tubes*, dekatrons and nixie tubes.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Thyratrons can also be used as triodes by operating them below their ignition voltage, allowing them to amplify analog signals as a self-quenching superregenerative detector in radio control receivers.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Hot-cathode, gas-discharge noise diodes were available in normal radio tube glass envelopes for frequencies up to UHF, and as long, thin glass tubes with a normal bayonet light bulb mount for the filament and an anode top cap, for SHF frequencies and diagonal insertion into a waveguide.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] They were filled with a pure inert gas such as neon because mixtures made the output temperature-dependent.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Their burning voltage was under 200 V, but they needed optical priming by an incandescent 2-watt lamp and a voltage surge in the 5-kV range for ignition.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] One miniature thyratron found an additional use as a noise source, when operated as a diode in a transverse magnetic field.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] In the mid-20th century, voltage-regulator tubes were commonly used.
[src:esd-protection-deep/gas-discharge-tube] Cathode sputtering is taken advantage of in the *Time Totalizer*, a metal-vapor coulometer-based elapsed time meter where the sputtered metal is deposited on a collector element whose resistance therefore decreases slowly.
[src:esd-protection-deep/human-body-model] The **human-body model** (**HBM**) is the most commonly used model for characterizing the susceptibility of an electronic device to damage from electrostatic discharge (ESD).
[src:esd-protection-deep/human-body-model] The model is a simulation of the discharge which might occur when a human touches an electronic device.
[src:esd-protection-deep/human-body-model] The HBM definition most widely used is the test model defined in the United States military standard, MIL-STD-883, Method 3015.9, Electrostatic Discharge Sensitivity Classification.
[src:esd-protection-deep/human-body-model] This method establishes a simplified equivalent electrical circuit and the necessary test procedures required to model an HBM ESD event.
[src:esd-protection-deep/human-body-model] An internationally widely used standard is JEDEC standard JS-001.
[src:esd-protection-deep/human-body-model] HBM is used primarily for manufacturing environments to quantify an integrated circuit to survive the manufacturing process.
[src:esd-protection-deep/human-body-model] A similar standard, IEC 61000-4-2, is used for system level testing and quantifies protection levels for a real world ESD event in an uncontrolled environment.
[src:esd-protection-deep/human-body-model] In both JS-001-2012 and MIL-STD-883H the charged human body is modeled by a 100 pF capacitor and a 1500 ohm discharging resistance.
[src:esd-protection-deep/human-body-model] During testing, the capacitor is fully charged to several kilovolts (2 kV, 4 kV, 6 kV and 8 kV are typical standard levels) and then discharged through the resistor connected in series to the device under test.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A **transient-voltage-suppression** (**TVS**) **diode**, also **transil**, **transorb** or **thyrector**, is an electronic component used to protect electronics from voltage spikes induced on connected wires.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] The device operates by shunting excess current when the induced voltage exceeds the avalanche breakdown potential.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] It is a clamping device, suppressing all overvoltages above its breakdown voltage.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] It automatically resets when the overvoltage goes away, but absorbs much more of the transient energy internally than a similarly rated crowbar device.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A transient-voltage-suppression diode may be either unidirectional or bidirectional.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A unidirectional device operates as a rectifier in the forward direction like any other avalanche diode, but is made and tested to handle very large peak currents.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A bidirectional transient-voltage-suppression diode can be represented by two mutually opposing avalanche diodes in series with one another and connected in parallel with the circuit to be protected.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] While this representation is schematically accurate, physically the devices are now manufactured as a single component.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A transient-voltage-suppression diode can respond to over-voltages faster than other common over-voltage protection components such as varistors or gas discharge tubes.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] The actual clamping occurs in roughly one picosecond, but in a practical circuit the inductance of the wires leading to the device imposes a higher limit.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] This makes transient-voltage-suppression diodes useful for protection against very fast and often damaging voltage transients.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] These fast over-voltage transients are present on all distribution networks and can be caused by either internal or external events, such as lightning or motor arcing.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] Transient voltage suppressors will fail if they are subjected to voltages or conditions beyond those that the particular product was designed to accommodate.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] There are three key modes in which the TVS will fail: short, open, and degraded device.
[src:esd-protection-deep/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] TVS diodes are sometimes referred to as transorbs, from the Vishay trademark *TransZorb*.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] **voltage-dependent resistor (VDR)**) is a surge protecting electronic component with an electrical resistance that varies with the applied voltage.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] It has a nonlinear, non-ohmic current–voltage characteristic that is similar to that of a diode.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Unlike a diode however, it has the same characteristic for both directions of traversing current.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Traditionally, varistors were constructed by connecting two rectifiers, such as the copper-oxide or germanium-oxide rectifier in antiparallel configuration.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] At low voltage the varistor has a high electrical resistance which decreases as the voltage is raised.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Modern varistors are primarily based on sintered ceramic metal-oxide materials which exhibit directional behavior only on a microscopic scale.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] This type is commonly known as the **metal-oxide varistor** (**MOV**).
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Varistors are used as control or compensation elements in circuits either to provide optimal operating conditions or to protect against excessive transient voltages.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] When used as protection devices, they shunt the current created by the excessive voltage away from sensitive components when triggered.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The name *varistor* is a portmanteau of *varying resistor*.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The term is only used for non-ohmic varying resistors.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Variable resistors, such as the potentiometer and the rheostat, have ohmic characteristics.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The development of the varistor, in form of a new type of rectifier based on a cuprous oxide (Cu2O) layer on copper, originated in the work by L.O.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The copper-oxide varistor exhibited a varying resistance in dependence on the polarity and magnitude of applied voltage.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] It was constructed from a small copper disk, on one side of which, a layer of cuprous oxide was formed.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] This arrangement provides low resistance to current flowing from the semiconducting oxide to the copper side, but a high resistance to current in the opposite direction, with the instantaneous resistance varying continuously with the voltage applied.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] In the 1930s, small multiple-varistor assemblies of a maximum dimension of less than one inch and apparently indefinite useful lifetime found application in replacing bulky electron tube circuits as modulators and demodulators in carrier current systems for telephonic transmission.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Other applications for varistors in the telephone plant included protection of circuits from voltage spikes and noise, as well as click suppression on receiver (*ear-piece*) elements to protect users' ears from popping noises when switching circuits.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] These varistors were constructed by layering an even number of rectifier disks in a stack and connecting the terminal ends and the center in an anti-parallel configuration, as shown in the photo of a Western Electric Type 3B varistor of June 1952 (below).
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The Western Electric type 500 telephone set of 1949 introduced a dynamic loop equalization circuit using varistors that shunted relatively high levels of loop current on short central office loops to adjust the transmission and receiving signal levels automatically.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] On long loops, the varistors maintained a relatively high resistance and did not alter the signals significantly.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Another type of varistor was made from silicon carbide (SiC) by R.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] It was used to guard telephone lines from lightning.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] In the early 1970s, Japanese researchers recognized the semiconducting electronic properties of zinc oxide (ZnO) as being useful as a new varistor type in a ceramic sintering process, which exhibited a voltage-current function similar to that of a pair of back-to-back Zener diodes.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] This type of device became the preferred method for protecting circuits from power surges and other destructive electric disturbances, and became known generally as the metal-oxide varistor (MOV).
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The randomness of orientation of ZnO grains in the bulk of this material provided the same voltage-current characteristics for both directions of current flow.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The most common modern type of varistor is the metal-oxide varistor (MOV).
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] This type contains a ceramic mass of zinc oxide (ZnO) grains, in a matrix of other metal oxides, such as small amounts of bismuth, cobalt, manganese oxides, sandwiched between two metal plates, which constitute the electrodes of the device.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The boundary between each grain and a neighbor forms a diode junction, which allows current to flow in only one direction.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The accumulation of randomly oriented grains is electrically equivalent to a network of back-to-back diode pairs, each pair in parallel with many other pairs.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] When a small voltage is applied across the electrodes, only a tiny current flows, caused by reverse leakage through the diode junctions.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] When a large voltage is applied, the diode junction breaks down due to a combination of thermionic emission and electron tunneling, resulting in a large current flow.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The result of this behavior is a nonlinear current-voltage characteristic, in which the MOV has a high resistance at low voltages and a low resistance at high voltages.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] A varistor remains non-conductive as a shunt-mode device during normal operation when the voltage across it remains well below its "clamping voltage", thus varistors are typically used for suppressing line voltage surges.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Varistors can fail for either of two reasons.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] A catastrophic failure occurs from not successfully limiting a very large surge from an event like a lightning strike, where the energy involved is many orders of magnitude greater than the varistor can handle.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Follow-through current resulting from a strike may melt, burn, or even vaporize the varistor.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The probability of catastrophic failure can be reduced by increasing the rating, or using specially selected MOVs in parallel.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Cumulative degradation occurs as more surges happen.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] For historical reasons, many MOVs have been incorrectly specified allowing frequent swells to also degrade capacity.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] In this condition the varistor is not visibly damaged and outwardly appears functional (no catastrophic failure), but it no longer offers protection.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Eventually, it proceeds into a shorted circuit condition as the energy discharges create a conductive channel through the oxides.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The main parameter affecting varistor life expectancy is its energy (Joule) rating.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Increasing the energy rating raises the number of (defined maximum size) transient pulses that it can accommodate exponentially as well as the cumulative sum of energy from clamping lesser pulses.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] As these pulses occur, the "clamping voltage" it provides during each event decreases, and a varistor is typically deemed to be functionally degraded when its "clamping voltage" has changed by 10%.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Manufacturer's life-expectancy charts relate current, severity, and number of transients to make failure predictions based on the total energy dissipated over the life of the part.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] In consumer electronics, particularly surge protectors, the MOV varistor size employed is small enough that eventually failure is expected.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Other applications, such as power transmission, use VDRs of different construction in multiple configurations engineered for long life span.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] MOVs are specified according to the voltage range that they can tolerate without damage.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Other important parameters are the varistor's energy rating in joules, operating voltage, response time, maximum current, and breakdown (clamping) voltage.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Energy rating is often defined using standardized transients such as 8/20 microseconds or 10/1000 microseconds, where 8 microseconds is the transient's front time and 20 microseconds is the time to half value.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Typical capacitance for consumer-sized (7–20 mm diameter) varistors are in the range of 100–2,500 pF.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Smaller, lower-capacitance varistors are available with capacitance of ~1 pF for microelectronic protection, such as in cellular phones.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] These low-capacitance varistors are, however, unable to withstand large surge currents simply due to their compact PCB-mount size.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The response time of the MOV is not standardized.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The sub-nanosecond MOV response claim is based on the material's intrinsic response time, but will be slowed down by other factors such as the inductance of component leads and the mounting method.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] That response time is also qualified as insignificant when compared to a transient having an 8 µs rise-time, thereby allowing ample time for the device to slowly turn-on.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] When subjected to a very fast, <1 ns rise-time transient, response times for the MOV are in the 40–60 ns range.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] A typical surge protector power strip is built using MOVs.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Low-cost versions may use only one varistor, from the hot (live, active) to the neutral conductor.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] A better protector contains at least three varistors; one across each of the three pairs of conductors.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Some standards mandate a triple varistor scheme so that catastrophic MOV failure does not create a fire hazard.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] While a MOV is designed to conduct significant power for very short durations (about 8 to 20 microseconds), such as caused by lightning strikes, it typically does not have the capacity to conduct sustained energy.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Under normal utility voltage conditions, this is not a problem.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] However, certain types of faults on the utility power grid can result in sustained over-voltage conditions.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Examples include a loss of a neutral conductor or shorted lines on the high voltage system.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Application of sustained over-voltage to a MOV can cause high dissipation, potentially resulting in the MOV device catching fire.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] The National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) has documented many cases of catastrophic fires that have been caused by MOV devices in surge suppressors, and has issued bulletins on the issue.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] A series connected thermal fuse is one solution to catastrophic MOV failure.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Varistors with internal thermal protection are also available.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] There are several issues to be noted regarding behavior of transient voltage surge suppressors (TVSS) incorporating MOVs under over-voltage conditions.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Depending on the level of conducted current, dissipated heat may be insufficient to cause failure, but may degrade the MOV device and reduce its life expectancy.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] If excessive current is conducted by a MOV, it may fail catastrophically to an open circuit condition, keeping the load connected but now without any surge protection.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] A user may have no indication that the surge suppressor has failed.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Under the right conditions of over-voltage and line impedance, it may be possible to cause the MOV to burst into flames, the root cause of many fires which is the main reason for NFPA's concern resulting in UL1449 in 1986 and subsequent revisions in 1998 and 2009.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Properly designed TVSS devices must not fail catastrophically, instead resulting in the opening of a thermal fuse or something equivalent that only disconnects MOV devices.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] A MOV inside a transient voltage surge suppressor (TVSS) does not provide complete protection for electrical equipment.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] In particular, it provides no protection from sustained over-voltages that may result in damage to that equipment as well as to the protector device.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Other sustained and harmful over-voltages may be lower and therefore ignored by a MOV device.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] A varistor provides no equipment protection from inrush current surges (during equipment startup), from overcurrent (created by a short circuit), or from voltage sags (brownouts); it neither senses nor affects such events.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Another method for suppressing voltage spikes is the transient-voltage-suppression diode (TVS).
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Although diodes do not have as much capacity to conduct large surges as MOVs, diodes are not degraded by smaller surges and can be implemented with a lower "clamping voltage".
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] MOVs degrade from repeated exposure to surges and generally have a higher "clamping voltage" so that leakage does not degrade the MOV.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Both types are available over a wide range of voltages.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] MOVs tend to be more suitable for higher voltages, because they can conduct the higher associated energies at less cost.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Another type of transient suppressor is the gas-tube suppressor.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] This is a type of spark gap that may use air or an inert gas mixture and often, a small amount of radioactive material such as Ni-63, to provide a more consistent breakdown voltage and reduce response time.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] Unfortunately, these devices may have higher breakdown voltages and longer response times than varistors.
[src:esd-protection-deep/varistor] However, they can handle significantly higher fault currents and withstand multiple high-voltage hits (for example, from lightning) without significant degradation.
